        id: 'cursor-adv-3', slug: 'memories', moduleSlug: 'advanced', toolSlug: 'cursor',
        title: 'Memories & Persistent Context', description: 'Use Memories to build a persistent knowledge base that improves AI responses over time.',
        order: 3, xpReward: 70, estimatedMinutes: 14,
        content: [
          { type: 'markdown', content: '# Memories & Persistent Context\n\nMemories allow Cursor to remember facts from your conversations and apply them in future sessions. Instead of repeating context every time, Cursor builds a persistent knowledge base for each project.\n\n## How Memories Work\n\n1. During a conversation, Cursor identifies important facts and preferences\n2. These are saved as "memories" that persist across sessions\n3. Future AI responses automatically reference relevant memories\n4. You can review, edit, and delete memories at any time\n\n## What Gets Remembered\n\n- **Project conventions**: "We use Zustand for state management, not Redux"\n- **Architecture decisions**: "The auth module uses JWTs stored in httpOnly cookies"\n- **Personal preferences**: "Always use arrow functions and Tailwind utility classes"\n- **Team standards**: "All API responses follow the { data, error, status } format"\n- **Bug context**: "The search indexer has a known race condition during rebuilds"' },
          { type: 'markdown', content: '## Managing Memories\n\n- **View all memories**: Settings > Memories, or ask "What do you remember about this project?"\n- **Add explicitly**: Tell Cursor "Remember that we use Vitest, not Jest"\n- **Delete incorrect ones**: Remove any outdated or wrong memories from settings\n- **Project-scoped**: memories are tied to the project, not global\n\n## Memories vs Cursor Rules\n\n| | Cursor Rules | Memories |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Source** | You write `.cursorrules` manually | Cursor learns from conversations |\n| **Scope** | Entire project, all users | Your sessions only |\n| **Format** | Structured rules file | Individual facts |\n| **Best for** | Team conventions, style guides | Project-specific knowledge, personal preferences |\n\n## Best Practices\n\n- **Correct bad memories early**: if Cursor remembers something wrong, delete it\n- **Use both**: Cursor Rules for team conventions + Memories for evolving project knowledge\n- **Be explicit**: say "Remember this" when you share important context\n- **Review periodically**: clean up outdated memories as the project evolves' },
          { type: 'callout', variant: 'tip', content: 'Memories compound over time. The longer you work on a project with Cursor, the more it understands your conventions, patterns, and preferences without you having to repeat them.' },
        ],
