        id: 'cursor-adv-5', slug: 'cursor-rules-advanced', moduleSlug: 'advanced', toolSlug: 'cursor',
        title: 'Cursor Rules & .cursorrules', description: 'Create project-specific AI instructions that enforce team conventions and improve code generation.',
        order: 5, xpReward: 75, estimatedMinutes: 15,
        content: [
          { type: 'markdown', content: '# Cursor Rules & .cursorrules\n\nCursor Rules are project-level instructions stored in a `.cursorrules` file at your repository root. Every AI interaction — Chat, Composer, and Agent Mode — reads these rules before generating a response.\n\n## Why Rules Matter\n\nWithout rules, Cursor relies on its general training. With rules, it generates code that matches *your* project\'s conventions from the first try.\n\n## File Location & Hierarchy\n\n| File | Scope | Priority |\n|------|-------|----------|\n| `.cursorrules` (project root) | Entire project | Highest |\n| `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` | Scoped rules with glob patterns | High — applies only to matched files |\n| Global settings | All projects | Lowest |\n\nScoped rules (`.mdc` files) let you set different instructions for different parts of your project — e.g., one set for the backend and another for the frontend.' },
          { type: 'code', language: 'markdown', code: '---\ndescription: Backend API conventions\nglobs: src/api/**/*.ts, src/services/**/*.ts\nalwaysApply: false\n---\n\nYou are working on a Node.js/Express backend with TypeScript.\n\nRules:\n- Use async/await for all asynchronous code (never raw Promises)\n- Validate all request inputs with Zod schemas\n- Return errors using the AppError class from @/lib/errors\n- Every service method must have a JSDoc comment\n- Use dependency injection via constructor parameters\n- Log with the structured logger from @/lib/logger (never console.log)\n- Database queries go in repository classes, never in services\n- All endpoints must have rate limiting applied', filename: '.cursor/rules/backend.mdc' },
          { type: 'code', language: 'markdown', code: '---\ndescription: React component conventions\nglobs: src/components/**/*.tsx, src/app/**/*.tsx\nalwaysApply: false\n---\n\nYou are working on a Next.js 14 app with React and Tailwind CSS.\n\nRules:\n- Use server components by default; add "use client" only when needed\n- Style with Tailwind utility classes (no CSS modules or styled-components)\n- Use the cn() helper from @/lib/utils for conditional class names\n- Colocate types in the same file unless shared across components\n- Use React.forwardRef for all reusable UI components\n- Prefer composition over prop drilling\n- All interactive components need aria labels and keyboard support', filename: '.cursor/rules/frontend.mdc' },
          { type: 'markdown', content: '## Writing Effective Rules\n\n### Do\n- Be specific: name exact libraries, patterns, and file paths\n- Include do/don\'t pairs for clarity\n- Reference real files in your project (`see src/lib/errors.ts for the AppError class`)\n- Keep rules under 1000 tokens for best adherence\n\n### Don\'t\n- Write vague instructions like "write good code"\n- Duplicate rules that are already in your linter config\n- Add contradictory rules between scoped files\n- Include sensitive information (API keys, secrets)' },
          { type: 'callout', variant: 'tip', content: 'Run the command "Cursor: Debug Cursor Rules" from the command palette to see which rules are active for the current file. This is invaluable for debugging why the AI isn\'t following a specific convention.' },
        ],
